--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, Rj &lt;rasterer@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; My two cents then:  it depends on the purpose of the announcement how best to go about the experiment.  If the purpose is to confirm to yourself or others that this was a valid prediction, or be able to make a case for there being something to this ITC stuff, or to have a prediction you can wave in the face of them darned skepdicks, then specifics have to be presented before the event.
&gt; 
&gt; If the purpose is not to do any of those things, but just try to see for yourself &#39;what works&#39;, then it doesn&#39;t much matter whether you give details after the event, or even bothering announcing the event at all.
&gt; 
&gt; So the only confusing part is why announce the event at all, if no details are given before it takes place?  Besides, if the details might help save someone from harm, it would be really a bad thing to do to keep them to yourself, wouldn&#39;t it?
&gt; 
&gt; Personally, if I thought I was getting predictions of future events that might cause harm to someone, I&#39;d be posting those details far and wide, in the hope of helping who I can.  Not doing that... well, I just hope the person doesn&#39;t believe in karma.
